Subject:    <a href="?t=95837890400020&r=1&w=2">gratuitious munging of ats in domain names</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837785600026&r=1&w=2">mailrus!emv () csd1 ! milw ! wisc ! edu  (Edward Vielmetti)</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198809">1988-09-19 1:05:27</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783026969&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783026969&q=raw">body</a>]</b>


(hope this makes it over the atlantic)

I just saw a piece of mail bounce because a mailer along the way
mis-handled an @.  Some headers for your perusal:


Received: by umix.cc.umich.edu (5.54/umix-2.0)
      id AA13705; Sun, 18 Sep 88 09:33:19 EDT
Message-Id: &lt;8809181333.AA13705@umix.cc.umich.edu&gt;
Received: from UKACRL.BITNET by CUNYVM.CUNY.EDU (IBM VM SMTP R1.1) with BSMTP id \
                0161; Sun, 18 Sep 88 09:36:42 EDT
Received: from RL.IB by UKACRL.BITNET (Mailer X1.25) with BSMTP id 2364; Sun,
 18 Sep 88 14:33:22 BST
Received: from RL.IB by UK.AC.RL.IB (Mailer X1.25) with BSMTP id 2363; Sun, 18
          Sep 88 14:33:22 BST
Via:      UK.AC.MAN.AT.STAR; 18 SEP 88 14:33:18 BST
Date:     18-SEP-1988 14:32:17 GMT
From: USER%STAR.@.MAN.AC.UK@CUNYVM.CUNY.EDU
To: username@UB.CC.UMICH.EDU
Sender: JANET "USER@UK.AC.MAN.AT.STAR" &lt;USER%STAR.@.MAN.AC.UK@CUNYVM.CUNY.EDU&gt;
Mailer:   Janet_Mailshr V3.1 (19-Aug-1988)

Unfortunately, it appears as though the mailer along
the way might have been umix - because of a ruleset
that looks like this:
	R$+ at $+	$1@$2
with the comment
	"at" -&gt; "@" for RFC 822

I've seen that sendmail ruleset in more than one package,
so I'm wondering what the recommendation should be:

	'at' not recommended as a component in domain names
	&lt;user at host&gt; syntax not supported any more

I'm sure that there are other domain name components that would
give existing software fits (imagine what a domain name like
'ibm.com.cc.umich.edu' would do to a mailer in the cc.umich.edu
domain that used the bind resolver routines.)

Comments?  I'm not sure how to proceed here, especially if the
UK mail ends up being important.

--Ed
Edward Vielmetti, U of Michigan computing center, mail group


